@node Overview "Overview"
A few years ago I bought a Texas Instruments TI-85 graphic calculator for my school maths and physics.  During my R.E. and other (just as exciting) exams, I wrote a simple program on it which listed all the factors of a given number.  This was useful for solving quadratic equations.
Anyway, one day I bought a Psion 3a palmtop computer and, because it had a far faster processor than my calculator, I thought it would be interesting to port the factor program over.  This was easy, apart from not having the same commands in OPL as in the calc, but I got there after a few hours.  As I'd expected, it was much faster at working out factors, but still left me waiting for the really big numbers.
Then I came to uni, and started coding in C - real speed on my real 68030!  A few days learning what the hell C was, and I had my first release of Factor, for the Amiga.
I was expecting it to be fast, but not this bloody fast!!  The code was in no way optimised, being pure ANSI so I could use it at uni, and it still works out all numbers INSTANTLY!  I still cant believe it.

After producing a very rough and ready Factor 1.0, I decided to smarten up the code a little and add a GUI - no real use, I just wanted to learn how to program one, so Factor 2.0 was born.  See @{"History" link history} for more info.

@endnode

@node Use
Factor is very simple to use:

  From WorkBench: 

    -  Double click it's icon.

    then:  Enter a number in the string gadget and either press <RETURN> 
           or click the "Do it" button

           If you want to save the list of factors, select Save from the
           File menu. (saves to whatever you set the filename requester
           at the bottom of the GUI to).

  From a command line:

    - type its name to bring up the @{"MUI" link mui} GUI

    - type its name, leave a space and then type the number (ie, pass the number as an argument)


  its that simple!

@endnode

